{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_douglasfir_ver01/data/sn86075189/00414211057/1958022101/0039.xml":{"full_text":"Editorial\nWhat's Behind Drive To Cut Income Tax?\nDemands for a cut in federal income taxes grow louder with each\npassing day. Politicians, business leaders, labor officials are all joining\nin the hue and cry. Here is a certain \"panacea\", many contend, to slow\nthe pace of the deepening recession, to aid the economy recover its\nmomentum toward a more prosperous future.\nNow I wonder. I've always looked up on \"panaceas\nway as I viewed castor oil as a kid.\nThere is no denying that the $600 individual exemption has become\nincreasingly unrealistic as inflation has, year after year, reduced the real\nvalue of the dollar. As a matter of equity, but not as a measure to stem\nthe recession, individual exemptions should be given a substantial upward\nboost.\nmuch the same\nHowever at this moment, neither increased exemptions nor substantial\ncuts in tax rates will do anything for many millions of Americans. For\nexample, reduced federal taxation would be completely meaningless to\nupwards of 25,000 Montanans who are currently jobless. Their employ\nment status has achieved for them all the \"benefits\" any Congressional tax\ncut authorization could possibly accomplish\u2014and then some.\nFor at least twenty million employed wage earners, any one of the\nseveral tax cuts being proposed might give them another $1.60 a week\nin \"take home\" pay. Precious few automobiles, household appliances, etc.,\nw\u00bbuld they be able to buy because of reduced income tax.\nI am not the only person capable of making these deductions. So I\nwonder what's really behind this drive to cut taxes?\nMaybe one clue is to be found in this week's U. S, NEWS WORLD\nREPORT. Says NEWS editor David Lawrence, \"if any reductions in tax\nrates are to be made, the taxes on corporations should be reduced from\n52 per cent to 35 per cent.\" And, on another page the NEWS gives its\nreason why corporate taxes should be cut: \"Tax cutting, to be really ef\nfective would need to reduce taxes on profits pf business or to make\nmore liberal the deductions allowed for writing off property so that business\nmen will be encouraged to speed new investment in machinery and build\nings and other\nIn view of industry already producing more than the American public\nhas the money to purchase, this line of reasoning has all the earmarks\nof the one used by the bankers' lobby before the 1957 Legislature, sic: \"if\nyou'll cut our tax classifications four times over, we'll raise our capitalization\nto more than make up the tax difference to the counties.\"\nThe bankers haven't made good on their promise.\nWithout a market, what reason is there for believing industry will do\nother than pocket any substantial tax cut they might receive?\nThe NEWS, in reporting to its business readers, unlike other tax-cut\nproponents, sees very little merit in extending tax relief to the citizenry\nas a whole, shrugging such ideas off as being of little value in perking up\nthe economy.\nThus it is this Editor approaches the matter of tax reduction at this\ntime with something of a jaundiced eye.\nWe need schools. We need housing. We need hospitals, and we need\nhuge resource development projects. All of these would require gigantic\namounts of labor; would pour needed dollars into the growing number of\nrecession-hit areas; would revive sagging purchasing power, and would\ngo far toward putting the national economy back on an even keel.\n\nIt seems obvious that private enterprise with profits at record heights\nhas not been able to give the shot in the arm necessary to stimulate and\ncarry our vastly expanding economy;\nw\u00e9alth and new jobs without stimulus from government in one form or\nanother. Private enterprise expands only as new life is pumped into it by\nthe co-operative contribution of all the people through their government.\nThe history of the country from its beginning records great strides by pri\nvate enterprise boosted by government activity whether it be resource de\nvelopment, land development or wars.\nPublic projects, unlike tax cuts (and I assume that to maintain any\nsemblance of a sound fiscal policy, we can't afford both), will restore\npurchasing power without which industry cannot\nmore sound approach to checking the recession.\nthat it can not create new\nsurvive, and appear the\nEaton Claims Dulles\nProlongs 'Cold War*\nTORONTO GLOBE MAIL, Feb. 11\nMONTREAL\u2014Cyrus Eaton, Nova\nScotia-born U, S. industrialist, today\nlambasted State Secretary Dulles\npetty tyrant in continually re-declar\ning the cold war and called for a new\nlook at international relations.\nMr. Eaton reviewed the armaments\nrace between the United States and\nRussia and found the only conclusion\nfrom all signs and portents is that\n\"the human race is hell-bent toward\nboth bankruptcy and suicide.\n\"I say all of this is incredible folly.\nI feel we ought to move vigorously and\nimmediately to avert the impending\ncatastrophe.\n\"I believe we can and must reach\na workable accommodation with the\nRussians. Certainly no issue now di\nviding the world looms so large\nto warrant the destruction of all that\ncivilization has produced.\"\nThe Cleveland industrialist, chair\nman of the board of the Chesapeake\nand Ohio Railway in the United\nStates, and of Steep Rock Mines, Ltd.,\nin Canada, spoke before the Canadian\nClub of Montreal.\n\"Our statesmen plainly have been\nstalling,\" said Mr .Eaton. \"They have\nplayed down the hazards to mankind\nof the insane armaments race. They\nhave seized upon every occasion to\nas a\nas\nfoment popular hatred of Russia.\"\nHe said the United States 12 years\nago declared cold war on Russia \"and\nthat has been the cardinal principle\nof U.S. foreign policy ever since.\nRussia had been an ally, Japan an\nenemy. Peace was made with Japan\nand friendship restored with her. But\nwe turned on Russia and challenged\nher to an armaments race.\n\"Because we alone knew the secrets\nof the A-bomb, we began the contest\nwith contempt for our opponent and\nconfidence in ourselves.\nft\n44\np\nChange of administration in the\nUnited States brought no alteration\nof the policy of baiting the Soviet\nbear, but an intense aggravation of it.\nMr. Dulles became the self-appoint\ned Soviet hate-monger and is still\nmaking a career of stirring up enmity\nand distrust between the Western and\nEastern worlds, Mr. Eaton said.\n\"The same Mr. Dulles who labels\nRussia and Red China as ruthless die\ntatorships has despotically decreed\nthat no U. S. observer or journalist\nshall go into China to get first-hand\ninformation for the United States\npeople on what is transpiring there.\n\"Let us no longer call ourselves the\nfree world when the petty tyrant of\nthe State Department can bring this\nto pass.\nRepr. LeRoy Anderson\nReports To You From\nThe Nation's Capito!\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\u2014In the sec\nond month of its sixth year in power,\nthe Administration has made a signifi\ncant about-face. It no longer is pay\ning even lip service to a balanced\nbudget. The President has proposed\na program of deficit spending. The\nproposal includes two billion dollars\nfor post offices, but not a penny for\nschool construction.\nThe changed attitude comes as the\nrecession deepens all over the coun\ntry. Steel production is down to 65\nper cent of capacity; construction,\nbuilding and many other industries\nare in distress and more than 4%\nmillion are unemployed. Montana is\nharder hit than many other states\nbecause the farm depression is piled\non a demoralized mining and smelt\ning industry, a despondent timber and\nwood products economy, and an oil\nproduction hard hit by foreign im\nports.\nCongress is looking at new meas\nures to help the economy. An income\ntax reduction is being considered. I\nhave introduced a public works bill\nand appropriations for government\nworks may be more liberal. Legisla\ntion comes slowly, though, and the\neconomic effects are even slower.\nWhat Montana really needs is some\ngood farm legislation. The farm bloc\nis pulling itself together for a real\ntry, but the threat of a Presidential\nveto hangs over the most promising\nproposals like a sword of Damocles.\nOil Imports\u2014 I met for a breakfast\ndiscussion with a group of other Con\ngressmen who are concerned over the\ngrowing threat to our independent\npetroleum producers that is result\ning from the flood of cheap foreign\noil pouring into America. Import\nquotas and duties to prevent killing\noff independent producers will be\nproposed at the time of consideration\nof the Reciprocal Trade Act.\nGas Bill\u2014 The general feeling here\nis that the natural gas bill has been\nknocked colder than a dead mackerel.\nThis bill, to remove natural gas prices\nfrom regulation by the Federal Power\nCommission, seems to have been\nhugged to death by its own overly\nardent supporters. A hundred thou\nsand dollars of Texas money has been\ncollected and earmarked in the public\nview for Congressional supporters of\nthe gas bill. Many who voted for it\nbefore say they cannot vote for it now\nand stand up to the suspicion of a\npayoff.\nLibrary Services- As a life-long\nresident of a rural area, I share with\nmost Montanans in those areas their\ninterest in maintaining and strength\nening the library facilities of\nState. I am supporting the full ap\npropriation for extension of public\nlibrary services in rural areas as a\npart of the Department of Health,\nEducation and Welfare budget\nquest.\nour\nre\nFarm Credit\u2014 An attempt is being\nmade to bring farm credit\ntions under the budget provisions of\nthe Government Corporation Control\nAct. The bill, HR 8332, which would\nundo the provision of law exempting\nfarm credit organizations,\nferred to the Committee on Govern\nment Operations, rather than the\nCommittee on Agriculture, which is\nmuch more sympathetic to agricul\nture. I joined with friends of\nwas re\nagri\nculture in both parties in a fight to\nkill this bill when I testified before\nthe Committee on Government Op\nerations this Tuesday.* Should the bill\nreach the floor of the House, we will\nmake a stiff fight to prevent its pas\nsage. The present system of farm\ncredit, developed over a period of\nmore than 40 years, is a very sound\noperation, with adequate audits, and\nI feel there is no excuse for the\nposed interference.\npro\nQUERIES\u2014 During the week, Con\nress an Metcalf and I met with 37\nus visitors from rural areas of\nMontana, who gave their views on\nP en di n g' legislation and allied matters,\nQ uer i es were made about durum\nw b ea t acreage incentives being in\ne ec the coming crop year. Last\nyear I introduced such legislation\nwas enacted into law. As\nresu ^t, adequate stock of durum\nv eat were raised and the carryover\nI s suc that no incentive legislation\nis deemed advisable this year. Any\ndurum wheat planted will be consid\nere( part the regular allotment.\n;i\nPublic Works Administration Act\nPWA?\nI have joined with\na num\nher of other Representatives and Sen\nators in seeking legislation to create\nWHA T DO YOU THINK?\nBy GRETCHEN G. BILLINGS\nEveryone will be happy to know\nthat Justice R. V. Bottomly is back at\nwork and feeling much better. Al\nready he has written a decision in an\nindustrial accident case that has im\nportant ramifications,\n\nThe VOICE this week is somewhat\nlopsided on coverage of meetings of\ncommittees in Helena, and we some\ntimes sorta sweat over these things.\nHowever, in talking it over we figured\nthese committees are going to be ex\nState In the \"Red\"\u2014\n(Continued From Page One)\nand \"prospects for correct\nlature\ning by legislation is denied until\nJanuary 1, 1959\",\nFollowing the appearance of the\nBoard of Equalization chairman the\ncouncil indulged in a debate as to\nwhether they should take action to\n\"freeze\" 10% of their funds.\nAlready budgeting a percentage of\ntheir appropriation for the next coun\ncil to operate on from January 1,\n1959 until June 30, it was not clear\nwhether the 10% figure was to be\nabove and beyond that figure or not.\nRep. Bernard opposed a \"freeze\"\nof the money on the basis they could\nunfreeze\" it and that he did not\n\na\nfavor any compulsory action before\nthe council had determined its finan\ncial needs to carry out the dictates\nof the legislature.\nof the appropriation was discarded.\nDave James said he was not going\nto spend over 90% of the council\nappropriation if he was part of a \"de\nmand\" that other departments cut.\nBarnard said \"If we cut our work\nwe are probably going to be adding\nto the over-all costs of government\".\nThe resolution passed, worded \"not\nless than 10 of their appropriation\nwould be saved.\nSenator Moritz said \"If we don't\nsave 10% we are going to have a\nhard time in the legislature\".\nAronson's Leadership\u2014\n(Continued From Page One)\n\"2. His persistent attempt through\nhis Chairman of the Unemployment\nCommission to conceal the true status\nof Montana's grave unemployment\npicture and his total failure to take\nany constructive steps to alleviate\nthe situation is appalling.\n3. His failure to apply to the state\naffairs ordinaty business methods\nwith the result that the five million\ndollar surplus he found in the gen\neral fund has disappeared, and in\nits place the fund will be in the red\nby at least four million dollars at the\nend of this fiscal year,\n\"4. The Governor's failure through\nhis Highway Commission to get the\ninterstate highway program under\nway with the result that in the con\n<4\ntinuing unemployment crisis, Mon\ntana has little work in progress and\nis one of the few states in the nation\nthere is a serious lag in the inter\nstate road program.\"\nAronson's\nlack of executive leadership is inex\ncusable under present emergency con\nditions,\" the Democratic Committee\nconcluded.\nGovernor\ncomplete\nfor 1958 in order to offset the growth\nof unemployment now attaining\nious proportions in Montana and\nthroughout the nation. My bill calls\nfor federal assistance of up to $500,\n000,000 to states and local govern\nments for the construction of need\u00e7d\npublic works and public improve\nments.\nFunds for Unemployed \u2014Congress\nhas passed and sent to the President\na resolution calling for $43.4 million\nin supplemental funds to firm up un\nemployment compensation funds for\nveterans and federal employes. The\nregular fund for this purpose is ex\npected to be depleted some time this\nweek. Of the supplemental funds,\n$25 million is slated for unemployed\nveterans and $18.4 for unemployed\nfederal workers.\nser\nQuotable Quote\nOur rights as individual human\nbeings depend on our willingness to\nact with respect for the rights of\nothers. And this principle applied to\nthe relationship of nations with\nanother is likewise the basis for\nworld at peace. DAG HAMMAR\nSKJOLD, UN Secretary General.\none\na\ntremely important during the next\nlegislature and our readers should be\ninterested in following rather closely\nthe things that take place in their\nmeetings.\nOne of the big objections I have\nhad to legislative interim committees\nhas been the lack of interest and\nknowledge over the countryside in\nwhat is going on. Then these interim\ncommittees come before the legisla\nture with the upper hand on their\nrecommendations because the people\nweren't aware of the thinking of the\ncommittee.\nThe Legislative Council and the\nTaxation and Education Commission\nhave allowed full coverage so far on\ntheir sessions.\nThe Legislative Council recognizes\nthe power they are going to have be\nfore the Legislature. They display\nlittle modesty when talking about the\nchance anything will have in the fields\nin which they are investigating, with\nout their approval.\nAlso, they feel, apparently, they\nwill perform in such a manner intefim\ncommittees will be continued as an\narm of the Legislature because they\nare seeking permanent quarters from\nthe Board of Examiners.\nTherefore the subjects they discuss\nshould merit your attention all during\nthe interim. It would be folly to figure\nyou can wait to make yourself heard\non any of the issues the Council\nstudies until the Legislature meets\nput to deny recommendations of a\ngroup that has spent two years study\ning them.\nI would not like to leave the im\npression I think the present council\nis going to come up with bad recom\nmendations. I would not want to be\nconsidered so foolish as to pretend I\nhave any idea what they are going\nto do.\nIn the first place they might kick\nme out of their meetings.\nIn the second place this committee\ndoes not want to be in the position\nof jeopardizing the possibility of fu\nture committees.\nWe do have, however, the experi\nence resulting from the 1951 Little\nHoover Committee, which in my esti\nmation was far from good. The pres\nent Legislative Council may also re\nmember that.\nThe point in this yak-yak is to\npoint out why we feel it is important\nthat you follow closely the activities\nof these groups, and if you have any\nstrong ideas on any of the subjects\nthey are studying you make yourself\nheard, because your chances will be\nbut small if you wait till January,\n1959.\nSenator Robert Durkee (D-Hill)\ntold me this week when he\nwas in\nHelena at the Legislative Council\nmeeting that he is strongly consider\ning filing for the Public Service Com\nmission. He\n4-year\nterm presently held by Ory Arm\nstrong.\nLooks as if the Democratic pri\nmary is going to be loaded with peo\nple going out for the nomination for\nthe four-year seat.\nThere has been a rumor that Arm\nstrong isn't going to run again for\nthe Public Service Commission I\nwould ask Ory, except he's such an old\npoker face. If he wasn't ready to give\nthe information you'd never even be\nable to make a good guess.\nUnited Press had a story saying\nArnold Olsen might seek the chief\njusticeship, I should have gone after\nthat scoop because I knew he had\nbeen asked by a number of people.\nAUTO MECHANICS\nAutomobile mechanics'make up by\nfar the largest repair occupation in\nthe labor force.\nTHE PEOPLE'S VOICE\nPublished Weekly by The People's\nVoice Publishing- Co., at 1205 Lockey\nStreet, Helena, Montana.\nHARRY L. BILLINGS, Editor\nEntered as Second Class Matter De\ncember 7, 1939, at the Post Office at\nHelena, Montana, under the Act of\nMarch 3, 1879.\nSubscription Price: $3.00 a Tear\nNo commercial Advertising except\nfrom Co-operative Business institu\ntions accepted. Rates on application.","height":"19992","width":"13653"}}
